<h1 class="hero-h">Are you ready <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">to roll out AI?</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Before you sign vendor contracts or write a roadmap, run through this 25-question readiness checklist. Each "no" is either a fix-it-first item or a reason to scope smaller. None of these are technology questions, they are organization questions, which is where AI rollouts actually live or die.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Use this before you build the roadmap</span><h2 class="h2">Answer honestly</h2><p class="body">Score yourself 0 or 1 on each. Anything 0 needs attention before, or alongside, rollout. Total score of 18+: you are ready. 12-17: ready with caveats. Below 12: fix the foundations before scaling AI usage.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Strategy &amp; leadership (5 questions)</span><h2 class="h2">Does the executive layer back this?</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>The CEO has stated, in writing, what AI is meant to accomplish at this company.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>There is a named human (not a committee) responsible for the AI rollout.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>That person has at least 8 hours per week of calendar dedicated to it.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>The exec team agrees on the top 3 outcomes that matter, and they are NOT "adopt AI."</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>There is a budget envelope set (even if rough) for tools, training, and external help.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Operations (6 questions)</span><h2 class="h2">Can the company absorb new tools?</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>There is at least one repeatable workflow documented per major function (sales, marketing, ops).</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We can name the 5 highest-leverage workflows where AI might help.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We have a way to measure outcomes (cycle time, output volume, hours saved), even crude.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We have shipped at least one internal tool/process change in the last 12 months that the team adopted.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Our team understands what "in production" means, i.e., the difference between a demo and a daily-use tool.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We have at least one person who can write a clear prompt and refine it iteratively.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Data &amp; security (5 questions)</span><h2 class="h2">Can your data go into AI tools?</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We know what data classes exist in our company (public, internal, confidential, regulated).</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We have written rules, even simple ones, for what data can go into external tools.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Our IT/security person knows what an enterprise AI platform's data handling looks like.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We are not currently in active remediation for a security incident.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>If regulated (HIPAA, SOC 2, PCI, etc.), we know which AI platforms have the appropriate attestations or agreements.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Tools &amp; access (4 questions)</span><h2 class="h2">Can people actually use the tools?</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Everyone in the affected workflows can be given an enterprise AI seat without procurement gymnastics.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Our IT setup will not block paste, file upload, or browser extensions the tools require.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Our SSO supports adding new SaaS tools without a 6-week IT project.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We are willing to pay for enterprise AI tier, not just free tiers.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Culture &amp; change (5 questions)</span><h2 class="h2">Will the team adopt this?</h2><ul class="checklist"><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>The team has been told (truthfully) that AI is meant to remove drudgery, not headcount.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Workflow owners are willing to change how they work, not just add a tool on the side.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We have a forum (Slack, regular standup, office hours) where prompts and tactics get shared.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>We are willing to publish a one-page AI policy and ask people to follow it.</span></li><li class="check-item"><span class="check-box"></span><span>Senior leaders are willing to use the tools themselves, visibly, not just sponsor the work.</span></li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What to do with your score</span><h2 class="h2">Three readiness levels</h2><h3 class="h3">18-25, Ready to scale</h3><p class="body">You have the foundations. Go straight to a 90-day rollout plan with three workflows running in parallel.</p><h3 class="h3">12-17, Ready with caveats</h3><p class="body">Pick one workflow, ship it well, and use the experience to build the foundations you are missing. Do not roll out everywhere yet.</p><h3 class="h3">Below 12, Fix foundations first</h3><p class="body">Spend 30-60 days on the missing foundations before adding AI scope. Almost always: assign a named owner, write the data rules, and ship one small thing.</p></div></section>

